fields.explanation: You use this to mark the topic of the sentence by placing it afterward the noun you would like to mark. We learned that a sentence like 大人です means "(somebody) is an adult" but how do we exactly say who is an adult? If I am referring to my friend けん, I can't just say けん大人です, this is grammatically incorrect and makes no sense. I would say けん<bold>は</bold>大人です. The は particle allows me to explain who or what is the topic of the sentence.
fields.name: は

fields.explanation: This turns a statement into a question. Just adding it alone at the end of a sentence can make a sentence go from, "It is cool." to "Is it cool?". It is often added after the polite form of words such as です but in informal situations can be added right after the word
fields.name: か

fields.question_text: コーヒー<answer>は</answer>おいしいです。

ズボン<answer>も</answer>かわいいです。
オーストラリアは大きいです<answer>か</answer>？
本はつまらないです<answer>か</answer>？

fields.content:
Many Japanese characters contain multiple kunyomi and onyomi readings. This presents a challenge as it can make it hard to know whether a word uses the onyomi or kunyomi reading of a kanji and which.



What is good news though is that there are general rules for when onyomi or kunyomi is used and there are many kanji that have multiple onyomi or kunyomi but only use one of them for the most part.



As a rule of thumb, words that only have kanji, no hiragana or katakana, and use multiple of them, use the onyomi readings. These words consisting multiple kanji and only kanji, are called compound words, or じゅくご in Japanese which we will refer to them by



Many Japanese words consist of just one kanji either with or without okurigana, the hiragana that comes after it, for example in the word 大きい meaning (big), the きい is called the okurigana. These words are generally read with the kunyomi reading. For the example the kunyomi of the "person" kanji (人) is ひと and the word 人 is read as ひと as the kunyomi is used.



As mentioned earlier these are just general rules but there are definitely a fair amount of exceptions. We will teach them to you as the words come along!
fields.header: How are they used in Vocabulary?

fields.content: Almost all Japanese consist of two readings known as Onyomi and Kunyomi. <subheader>Onyomi</subheader> As mentioned earlier, Kanji is a writing system that was adopted from Chinese. Naturally, some of these Chinese words were adopted as well and their readings were kept the same. This created the "onyomi" reading of the kanji. The literal meaning of onyomi is "sound reading" and that explains exactly what Onyomi is, the Chinese derived sound/reading of the kanji. <subheader>Kunyomi</subheader> Of course, when Chinese characters were adopted, Japanese already had it's own words. These Kanji characters were then also given the reading of the original Japanese words that had the same meaning. Essentially, kunyomi is the original Japanese reading.

Let's take a look at the kanji for mountain, 山. This character's chinese reading is shān and when this character became integrated into Japanese kanji it took the Onyomi (Chinese derived reading) さん(san). See the similarity? At the same time, in Japanese there was already a word for mountain called やま(yama). So since the Chinese character 山 meant "mountain" and the word for mountain in Japnaese was やま, the kanji 山 was given the reading やま!

Many Japanese characters contain multiple kunyomi and onyomi readings. This presents a challenge as it can make it hard to know whether a word uses the onyomi or kunyomi reading of a kanji and which.



What is good news though is that there are general rules for when onyomi or kunyomi is used and there are many kanji that have multiple onyomi or kunyomi but only use one of them for the most part.



As a rule of thumb, words that only have kanji, no hiragana or katakana, and use multiple of them, use the onyomi readings. These words consisting multiple kanji and only kanji, are called compound words, or じゅくご in Japanese which we will refer to them by



Many Japanese words consist of just one kanji either with or without okurigana, the hiragana that comes after it, for example in the word 大きい meaning (big), the きい is called the okurigana. These words are generally read with the kunyomi reading. For the example the kunyomi of the "person" kanji (人) is ひと and the word 人 is read as ひと as the kunyomi is used.



As mentioned earlier these are just general rules but there are definitely a fair amount of exceptions. We will teach them to you as the words come along!
